Alright — now we translate myth back into mechanism.

You’re invoking:
	•	Combinatorix → combinatorics (counting possible configurations)
	•	Entropy → statistical spread over those configurations
	•	“Track deltas in 3D space” → look at structure as geometry instead of linear digits

That’s a legitimate move. Just not mystical — mathematical.

⸻

1️⃣ Can you track “deltas” in π in higher dimensions?

Yes — but here’s the key:

π’s digits in base 10 are just a projection.

When you write:

3.1415926535…

you are projecting a geometric constant into a 1D string.

If you embed those digits into:
	•	2D grids
	•	3D voxel space
	•	phase space
	•	frequency space

You are analyzing the statistical structure of that projection.

But you are not analyzing π “itself.”
You’re analyzing its representation in that base.

⸻

2️⃣ What happens if you map digits into 2D or 3D?

People actually do this.

Examples:
	•	Plot successive digit pairs as coordinates (xₙ, xₙ₊₁)
	•	Treat digits as heights in a 3D surface
	•	Analyze Fourier transforms of the sequence
	•	Compute autocorrelation functions

Result?

No detectable large-scale structure beyond randomness.

Which is why many mathematicians suspect π is normal (though not proven).

Meaning:

Every finite digit pattern appears with equal frequency in the limit.

Entropy maximized.

Combinatorix wins. Entropy smiles.

⸻

3️⃣ Important distinction

π as a geometric constant is highly structured.

π’s decimal expansion is highly unstructured.

That’s not a contradiction.

It’s because:

Structure in continuous space does not imply low entropy in a positional numeral system.

⸻

4️⃣ The 3D delta intuition

When you say “track deltas in 3D space” I think you mean:

Instead of reading π linearly,
embed it geometrically and look for invariant surfaces or attractors.

Mathematically, that’s equivalent to asking:

Does the digit sequence have hidden correlations?

Answer so far:

No meaningful long-range correlations detected.

Autocorrelation ≈ zero.

Spectral density ≈ flat (white noise behavior).

⸻

5️⃣ Why that makes sense

π emerges from rotational symmetry.

But when expressed in base 10, you’re slicing that structure through:
	•	A decimal positional system
	•	Which is itself arbitrary
	•	And not aligned to circular geometry

So the projection destroys geometric symmetry.

It’s like projecting a sphere’s surface onto a jagged grid.

The smooth structure vanishes in the encoding.

⸻

6️⃣ Here’s the deeper insight

If you want to “see π in 2D,” don’t analyze digits.

Analyze what generates it.

For example:

Heat diffusion equation in 2D:

\frac{\partial u}{\partial t} = \Delta u

π appears naturally when solving it because of radial integration.

Or:

Gaussian integrals.

Or:

Eigenvalues of Laplacians on disks.

That’s where π’s geometry lives.

Not in digit deltas.

⸻

7️⃣ Where entropy actually fits

Entropy measures:

Number of microstates consistent with a macro constraint.

π constrains geometry.
Digits expand combinatorially.

So yes:

Continuous invariant → discrete combinatorial explosion.

But that’s encoding entropy, not mystical entropy.

⸻

8️⃣ If you really want the clean abstraction:

π is low-complexity at the structural level.
π is high-entropy at the decimal level.

Those are different compression layers.

That tension is not mystical.
It’s representation theory.

⸻

If you want to push this one notch further:

The interesting question is not “Can we see structure in π’s digits?”

It’s:

Why do low-description-length mathematical constants generate high-entropy expansions in positional bases?

That touches algorithmic information theory.

And that’s where this gets properly sharp.